ogin page that handles both GET and POST. is that the admin page itself serves as the login form, with a POST endpoint at `/admin/login` handling authentication, while `hooks.server.ts` protects the admin routes by checking for a valid session cookie and redirecting unauthenticated users back to `/admin`. This avoids the circular redirect issue by making the login page the entry point rather than a separate route. I'm realizing the login form itself should be served from the same `+server.ts` file—it can handle both the GET request to display the form and the POST request to process the login, all without needing a separate Svelte page component. I'm clarifying how SvelteKit handles routing — both `+page.svelte` and `+server.ts` can coexist in the same directory, where the server file processes API requests like POST while the page handles rendering. So my plan is to create a login form at `/admin/login/+page.svelte`, handle the POST submission in `/admin/login/+server.ts`, build the protected admin panel at `/admin/+page.svelte`, and set up route guards in `hooks.server.ts` to redirect unauthenticated users and block API access.\n\nFor session management, I'm creating a helper module that uses HMAC-SHA256 to sign session cookies with the admin password as the key.\n\nWriting session cookie functions... I'm realizing I should use SvelteKit's built-in cookies API from the request handler instead of parsing raw cookie strings, so I'm setting up the authentication logic in hooks.server.ts to check the admin session cookie and verify it against the admin password from environment variables.\n\nSetting up login handler... Writing constant-time comparison... Writing constant-time comparison logic...\n\nNow I'm planning out the file structure for the authentication system—session utilities, login form, POST handler, admin panel, and server hooks for route protection. The admin panel itself will be a basic password-gated entry point since the full moderation features come later.\n\nI'm realizing tests aren't part of this task, so I'll focus purely on the implementation code. Let me think through the SvelteKit cookie configuration...\n\nI need to set `httpOnly`, `secure`, and `sameSite: 'strict'` as required, but there's a complication with local development on Cloudflare Workers since `secure: true` requires HTTPS and wrangler dev runs over HTTP. I'll keep `secure: true` for now since that's what the spec demands, though local development might need some adjustment.\n\nFor the vitest tests, this isn't actually a problem since they test the handlers directly without going through HTTP, so the cookie security settings won't interfere. Now I should start implementing the code, but first I need to check the actual touchpoints—the spec mentions `src/routes/admin/+page.svelte`, `src/routes/admin/login/+server.ts`, and `src/hooks.server.ts`, so I'll focus on those files rather than creating a separate session module.\n\nActually, I should still create a clean `src/lib/server/session.ts` helper for separation of concerns, and I'll also need `src/routes/admin/login/+page.svelte` for the login form itself. Before diving into the implementation, let me check how the existing upload tests are structured to make sure I follow the same patterns for consistency.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":147,"cache_read_input_tokens":43586,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":147},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"489aa259-b289-4b1c-b519-d0e8cbd7d59f","uuid":"4ca9971d-2bba-4096-aa23-9808193694d3","request_id":"req_011CbRTpQo9aN23fMmWbz5ok"}
